{"type": "user", "message": {"role": "user", "content": [{"tool_use_id": "chatcmpl-tool-81b97a7f930ea70b", "type": "tool_result", "content": "Date of publication xxxx 00, 0000, date of current version xxxx 00, 0000.\nDigital Object Identifier 10.1109/ACCESS.2024.0429000\n\nPseudo-label distillation for discriminative\nanomalous sound detection\nTAKUYA FUJIMURA1 AND TOMOKI TODA1 , (Senior Member, IEEE)\n\n1\n\nNagoya University, Nagoya 464-8601, Japan\n\nCorresponding author: Takuya Fujimura (e-mail: fujimura.takuya@g.sp.m.is.nagoya-u.ac.jp).\n\narXiv:2607.16678v1 [eess.AS] 18 Jul 2026\n\nThis work was partly supported by JSPS KAKENHI Grant Number JP25KJ1439.\n\nABSTRACT Discriminative anomalous sound detection (ASD) methods train a feature extractor through\na classification task using machine-information labels. They then detect anomalies in the resulting feature\nspace based on distances to normal samples. The discriminative feature space effectively captures machine\ncharacteristics, leading to high ASD performance. However, this approach benefits from detailed labels,\nwhich are costly to obtain. An alternative is a self-supervised learning (SSL)-based label-free approach.\nThis approach directly uses SSL features for ASD and has shown competitive performance. However, SSL\nmodels are typically large and computationally expensive. To address these problems, we propose a simple\npseudo-label distillation framework. The proposed method generates pseudo labels from SSL features and\ntrains a compact discriminative feature extractor using these pseudo labels. To suppress the effect of noise on\npseudo-label generation, we also propose lightweight noise-robust feature transformation (NRFT) methods\nutilizing a small amount of clean machine-sound data or isolated noise data. We conducted comprehensive\nevaluations and analyses on the DCASE 2020–2025 Task 2 datasets using four SSL models. The results\ndemonstrate that pseudo-label distillation not only transfers the performance of SSL models to a compact\nmodel but also further improves performance by leveraging available coarse labels and data augmentation.\nAlso, our NRFT methods provide further gains.\nINDEX TERMS Anomalous sound detection, discriminative learning, pseudo label, self-supervised learning\n\nI. INTRODUCTION\n\nAnomalous sound detection (ASD) plays an important role\nin machine condition monitoring by automatically detecting\nmechanical failures from acoustic signals emitted by machines [1]–[6]. Since it is difficult to collect rare and diverse\nanomalous sounds, the ASD task is typically formulated in\nan unsupervised setting, in which only normal sounds are\navailable for system development.\nASD systems typically consist of a frontend and a backend [7]. The frontend first extracts features from input machine sounds. The backend then computes an anomaly score\nbased on the nearest-neighbor distance between a test sample\nand the normal training samples in the feature space. In this\nframework, anomalous sounds are expected to be distant from\nthe normal sounds in the feature space and yield high anomaly\nscores. Therefore, it is crucial to construct a feature space\nthat effectively captures the differences between normal and\nanomalous sounds.\nThere are two representative frontend approaches: discriminative learning [8]–[14] and self-supervised learning\nVOLUME 11, 2023\n\n(SSL) [15]–[21]. The discriminative approach uses machineinformation labels, such as machine type (e.g., gearbox and\nbearing) and operating parameters (e.g., voltage and rotation\nspeed). This approach trains a classification model on normal\ndata using these labels, and the intermediate discriminative\nfeatures are then used in the backend. These discriminative\nfeatures effectively capture rich machine-specific information and lead to high ASD performance [11]–[13]. However,\nthere is a clear trade-off between performance and annotation\ncost [22], [23]. For example, when each machine has its\nown microphone, as is often the case, machine-type labels\ncan be easily obtained from the microphone index. However,\nsuch coarse labels are insufficient for learning an effective\nfeature space. Detailed labels, such as operating parameters,\ncan greatly improve performance [22], [23], but collecting\nthem requires additional monitoring systems or costly human\nannotation.\nSSL is a promising label-free approach [15]–[18]. SSL\nmodels are trained on large-scale unlabeled audio datasets to\nlearn general-purpose audio representations [24]–[29]. These\n1\n\n\fT. Fujimura et al.: Pseudo-label distillation for discriminative anomalous sound detection\n\n1. Generate pseudo labels\nNormal\ndata\n\nSSL\nfrontend\n\nNoise-robust feature\ntransformation∗\n\nClustering\n(K-means)\n\nPseudo label\n\n2. Distillation through classification task\nNormal\ndata\n\nData aug.\n(mixup)\n\nDiscriminative\nfrontend\n\nLoss\n\nPseudo label\nCoarse label\n(machine type)\n\nFIGURE 1. Overview of pseudo-label distillation. First, SSL features are\nextracted and optionally further transformed into noise-robust features\n(∗: requires a small number of clean machine sounds or isolated noise\nsamples). Next, pseudo labels are generated by applying clustering to the\nresulting features. Finally, a compact discriminative frontend is trained\nusing the pseudo labels together with available coarse labels and data\naugmentation.\n\nrepresentations effectively capture acoustic characteristics\nand have achieved strong performance across various audio\ntasks, including ASD. Although discriminative fine-tuning\non machine sound datasets using machine-information labels\ncan further improve performance [19]–[21], the original SSL\nfeatures already provide competitive performance without\nusing any label information [15]–[17]. However, SSL models\nare computationally expensive. Typical SSL models [24],\n[25], [28], [29] have approximately 90M parameters, and recent scaled-up models exceed 1B parameters [26]. In contrast,\ntypical discriminative feature extractors [11], [12], [14], [22]\nhave only a few million parameters, corresponding to less\nthan 10% of the parameter count of a typical SSL model.\nIn this paper, we introduce pseudo-label distillation to\naddress the insufficient performance obtained using coarse\nlabels and the high computational cost of SSL models (see\nFig. 1). This approach first extracts SSL features from training\ndata consisting of normal machine sounds and then generates pseudo labels by applying clustering to the extracted\nfeatures. Next, a smaller discriminative frontend is trained\nusing these pseudo labels. During training, available coarse\nlabels (e.g., machine-type labels) and data augmentation are\njointly used to further improve performance. Additionally,\nwe propose lightweight noise-robust feature transformation\n(NRFT) methods as a preprocessing step to suppress the\neffects of noise contained in the training data. NRFT uses a\nlinear transformation estimated using a small amount of clean\nmachine-sound data or isolated noise data.\nThe pseudo-label distillation approach itself was proposed\nin our previous work [22]. Subsequent studies have also\nexplored related techniques, including iterative pseudo-label\ngeneration in a discriminative feature space [30], multipseudo-label assignment [31], and domain-adaptive pretraining of teacher SSL models [32]. In contrast, this paper focuses on the original, simple pseudo-label distillation framework and conducts comprehensive evaluations and analyses\nto provide a deeper understanding. Our contributions are\nsummarized as follows:\n• We conduct comprehensive evaluations across the\nDCASE 2020–2025 datasets using four state-of-the-art\n2\n\n(SOTA) SSL models. The experimental results show\nthat pseudo-label distillation effectively transfers the\nperformance of SSL models to smaller discriminative\nfrontends while reducing the number of parameters and\nmultiply-accumulate operations (MACs) to less than\n10% of those of the original SSL models.\n• We show that pseudo-label distillation can achieve even\nbetter performance than the original SSL models by\nutilizing available coarse labels and data augmentation.\n• We further show that the performance gains from\npseudo-label distillation are observed not only when\ntraining small discriminative frontends from scratch but\nalso when fine-tuning SSL models.\n• We propose lightweight NRFT methods that construct\nnoise-robust feature spaces for pseudo-label generation\nusing a small amount of clean machine sounds or isolated noise samples.\n1\n• We publish the code in ASDKit [7].\nII. RELATED WORK\n\nMany methods have been proposed to obtain effective feature spaces for ASD. Discriminative approaches have been\nimproved in terms of loss functions, data augmentation, and\nnetwork architectures. In terms of loss functions, angularmargin losses such as ArcFace [33] and AdaCos [34] have\nbeen commonly employed for the ASD task. These losses\nencourage the features of each class to form compact and\nwell-separated clusters, which has been shown to be effective\nfor the downstream ASD task [23]. In addition, less restrictive\nfeature distributions have been shown to further improve ASD\nperformance. Such distributions can be learned using Subcluster AdaCos (SCAC) [23], which introduces multiple class\ncenters for each class, and trainable class centers rather than\nfixed centers [7]. For data augmentation, mixup [35] has been\nwidely used and shown to improve ASD performance [7]. Regarding network architectures, lightweight CNN-based networks have been commonly used [2], [3], [11], [12], [14],\n[36]. The DCASE Challenge Task 2 baseline [2], [3] employed MobileNetV2 [36] with log-mel spectrogram input,\nand an extension using waveform input has been shown to\nimprove performance [14]. Multi-branch architectures comprising spectrogram and spectrum branches have also been\nwidely adopted [11], [12], with further improvements reported using multi-resolution spectrogram inputs [22]. These\ndiscriminative models are trained from scratch on machinesound datasets and are considerably more lightweight than\nSSL models.\nFor SSL-based approaches, many SSL models have been\nemployed for ASD. BEATs [24] is one of the most widely\nused SSL models for various audio tasks, including ASD [16],\n[17], [19], [37]. It is trained through masked audio prediction\nin a discrete token space, with the tokenizer and SSL model\niteratively updated through knowledge distillation. EAT [25]\nis another SSL model widely used for ASD [16], [17], [37]. It\n1 https://github.com/TakuyaFujimura/dcase-asd-toolkit\nVOLUME 11, 2023\n\n\fT. Fujimura et al.: Pseudo-label distillation for discriminative anomalous sound detection\n\nis based on a masked bootstrapping framework and employs\na CLS token and an utterance-level loss to capture global\ninformation. Dasheng is a recent large-scale SSL model with\napproximately 1.2B parameters. It is trained using a masked\nautoencoder framework on 272k hours of audio data. These\naudio SSL models are trained on diverse audio datasets\nspanning speech, music, and environmental sounds and have\nbeen shown to achieve better ASD performance than speechand music-specific SSL models [21], [27]. More recently,\nSSL models specifically designed for machine signals have\nalso been proposed [27], [38]. These models are designed\nto handle arbitrary sampling rates and have shown strong\nperformance on fault-diagnosis benchmarks. Despite these\nadvantages, the aforementioned general-purpose audio SSL\nmodels have still demonstrated comparable or better ASD\nperformance [27], highlighting their strong generalization\ncapabilities.\nIII. PSEUDO-LABEL DISTILLATION\nA. OVERVIEW\n\nPseudo-label distillation first extracts SSL features from normal training data. We employ the following four SSL models:\nBEATs [24] (BEATs_iter3.pt), a version of BEATs fine-tuned\nfor audio tagging (BEATs_iter3_plus_AS2M_finetuned_on_\nAS2M_cpt1.pt), EAT [25] (EAT-base_epoch10_pt.pt), and\nDasheng [26] (dasheng-1.2B). These SSL models receive a\nsequence of mel-spectrogram patches or segments and output\nthe corresponding feature sequence. For BEATs and Dasheng,\nwe average the SSL feature sequence to obtain a single feature\nvector for each audio sample, whereas for EAT, we use the\nCLS token. To generate pseudo labels, we apply k-means\nclustering, with the number of clusters determined from the\nnumber of training samples using the cluster ratio r. We\nevaluate several values of r, as well as an oracle setting in\nwhich the best value of r is selected separately for each\nmachine type.\nTo not only reduce computational cost but also further\nimprove performance, we jointly use available coarse labels\nduring pseudo-label distillation. In the experiments, we use\nthe machine-type labels provided in the DCASE datasets [1]–\n[6] as coarse labels. Using these coarse labels, we perform\nclustering separately for each coarse-label class and combine the resulting pseudo labels to construct a multi-class\nclassification task for distillation. For example, the DCASE\n2023 dataset contains 14 machine types, each with 1,000\nnormal training samples. Thus, setting r = 0.2% yields 2\npseudo-label classes per machine type, resulting in a multiclass classification task with 28 classes in total. Additionally,\nmotivated by the Noisy Student framework [39], we employ\nmixup as data augmentation during pseudo-label distillation.\nB. NOISE-ROBUST FEATURE TRANSFORMATION (NRFT)\n\nIn the experimental evaluations in Sect. IV, we show\nthat pseudo-label distillation can sometimes degrade performance. This degradation occurs because the training data\nconsist of noisy machine sounds, and the SSL features capture\nVOLUME 11, 2023\n\nnot only machine characteristics but also noise characteristics. When noise conditions vary across training samples and\nthe noise dominates the machine sound, the resulting pseudo\nlabels primarily reflect differences in noise conditions rather\nthan machine characteristics. Such noise-dependent pseudo\nlabels make the student frontend sensitive to noise variations,\nthereby degrading performance.\nTo address this issue, we propose a lightweight noiserobust feature transformation (NRFT) method for pseudolabel generation. In general, improving noise robustness requires auxiliary information about either noise or clean target\nsounds. In this work, we consider the setting of DCASE 2025\nTask 2 [6], where a small number of either clean machinesound samples or isolated noise samples are available for each\nmachine type.\nFor the case where clean machine sounds are available,\nwe propose a principal component analysis (PCA)-based\nsubspace projection. We first extract SSL features from the\nclean machine sounds and apply PCA to the extracted clean\nfeatures. We then construct a projection matrix V ∈ RD×K\nusing the top K principal components, where D denotes the\nfeature dimension. The SSL features of the noisy machine\nsounds in the training data are projected onto this subspace,\nand clustering is then performed to obtain pseudo labels. This\nprojection suppresses components that are less representative\nof the clean machine sounds and are therefore likely to reflect\nnoise-related variations.\nFor the case where isolated noise samples ar\nShell cwd was reset to /inspire/qb-ilm/project/video-generation/chenxie-25019/hyr/iHateTheWorld555.github.io", "is_error": false}]}, "parent_tool_use_id": null, "session_id": "19e31ec3-fea2-4fd0-b28f-598d48d170a2", "uuid": "2ee08c12-270a-44f7-a024-3f27b93c9efc", "timestamp": "2026-07-21T12:17:46.749Z", "tool_use_result": {"stdout": "Date of publication xxxx 00, 0000, date of current version xxxx 00, 0000.\nDigital Object Identifier 10.1109/ACCESS.2024.0429000\n\nPseudo-label distillation for discriminative\nanomalous sound detection\nTAKUYA FUJIMURA1 AND TOMOKI TODA1 , (Senior Member, IEEE)\n\n1\n\nNagoya University, Nagoya 464-8601, Japan\n\nCorresponding author: Takuya Fujimura (e-mail: fujimura.takuya@g.sp.m.is.nagoya-u.ac.jp).\n\narXiv:2607.16678v1 [eess.AS] 18 Jul 2026\n\nThis work was partly supported by JSPS KAKENHI Grant Number JP25KJ1439.\n\nABSTRACT Discriminative anomalous sound detection (ASD) methods train a feature extractor through\na classification task using machine-information labels. They then detect anomalies in the resulting feature\nspace based on distances to normal samples. The discriminative feature space effectively captures machine\ncharacteristics, leading to high ASD performance. However, this approach benefits from detailed labels,\nwhich are costly to obtain. An alternative is a self-supervised learning (SSL)-based label-free approach.\nThis approach directly uses SSL features for ASD and has shown competitive performance. However, SSL\nmodels are typically large and computationally expensive. To address these problems, we propose a simple\npseudo-label distillation framework. The proposed method generates pseudo labels from SSL features and\ntrains a compact discriminative feature extractor using these pseudo labels. To suppress the effect of noise on\npseudo-label generation, we also propose lightweight noise-robust feature transformation (NRFT) methods\nutilizing a small amount of clean machine-sound data or isolated noise data. We conducted comprehensive\nevaluations and analyses on the DCASE 2020–2025 Task 2 datasets using four SSL models. The results\ndemonstrate that pseudo-label distillation not only transfers the performance of SSL models to a compact\nmodel but also further improves performance by leveraging available coarse labels and data augmentation.\nAlso, our NRFT methods provide further gains.\nINDEX TERMS Anomalous sound detection, discriminative learning, pseudo label, self-supervised learning\n\nI. INTRODUCTION\n\nAnomalous sound detection (ASD) plays an important role\nin machine condition monitoring by automatically detecting\nmechanical failures from acoustic signals emitted by machines [1]–[6]. Since it is difficult to collect rare and diverse\nanomalous sounds, the ASD task is typically formulated in\nan unsupervised setting, in which only normal sounds are\navailable for system development.\nASD systems typically consist of a frontend and a backend [7]. The frontend first extracts features from input machine sounds. The backend then computes an anomaly score\nbased on the nearest-neighbor distance between a test sample\nand the normal training samples in the feature space. In this\nframework, anomalous sounds are expected to be distant from\nthe normal sounds in the feature space and yield high anomaly\nscores. Therefore, it is crucial to construct a feature space\nthat effectively captures the differences between normal and\nanomalous sounds.\nThere are two representative frontend approaches: discriminative learning [8]–[14] and self-supervised learning\nVOLUME 11, 2023\n\n(SSL) [15]–[21]. The discriminative approach uses machineinformation labels, such as machine type (e.g., gearbox and\nbearing) and operating parameters (e.g., voltage and rotation\nspeed). This approach trains a classification model on normal\ndata using these labels, and the intermediate discriminative\nfeatures are then used in the backend. These discriminative\nfeatures effectively capture rich machine-specific information and lead to high ASD performance [11]–[13]. However,\nthere is a clear trade-off between performance and annotation\ncost [22], [23]. For example, when each machine has its\nown microphone, as is often the case, machine-type labels\ncan be easily obtained from the microphone index. However,\nsuch coarse labels are insufficient for learning an effective\nfeature space. Detailed labels, such as operating parameters,\ncan greatly improve performance [22], [23], but collecting\nthem requires additional monitoring systems or costly human\nannotation.\nSSL is a promising label-free approach [15]–[18]. SSL\nmodels are trained on large-scale unlabeled audio datasets to\nlearn general-purpose audio representations [24]–[29]. These\n1\n\n\fT. Fujimura et al.: Pseudo-label distillation for discriminative anomalous sound detection\n\n1. Generate pseudo labels\nNormal\ndata\n\nSSL\nfrontend\n\nNoise-robust feature\ntransformation∗\n\nClustering\n(K-means)\n\nPseudo label\n\n2. Distillation through classification task\nNormal\ndata\n\nData aug.\n(mixup)\n\nDiscriminative\nfrontend\n\nLoss\n\nPseudo label\nCoarse label\n(machine type)\n\nFIGURE 1. Overview of pseudo-label distillation. First, SSL features are\nextracted and optionally further transformed into noise-robust features\n(∗: requires a small number of clean machine sounds or isolated noise\nsamples). Next, pseudo labels are generated by applying clustering to the\nresulting features. Finally, a compact discriminative frontend is trained\nusing the pseudo labels together with available coarse labels and data\naugmentation.\n\nrepresentations effectively capture acoustic characteristics\nand have achieved strong performance across various audio\ntasks, including ASD. Although discriminative fine-tuning\non machine sound datasets using machine-information labels\ncan further improve performance [19]–[21], the original SSL\nfeatures already provide competitive performance without\nusing any label information [15]–[17]. However, SSL models\nare computationally expensive. Typical SSL models [24],\n[25], [28], [29] have approximately 90M parameters, and recent scaled-up models exceed 1B parameters [26]. In contrast,\ntypical discriminative feature extractors [11], [12], [14], [22]\nhave only a few million parameters, corresponding to less\nthan 10% of the parameter count of a typical SSL model.\nIn this paper, we introduce pseudo-label distillation to\naddress the insufficient performance obtained using coarse\nlabels and the high computational cost of SSL models (see\nFig. 1). This approach first extracts SSL features from training\ndata consisting of normal machine sounds and then generates pseudo labels by applying clustering to the extracted\nfeatures. Next, a smaller discriminative frontend is trained\nusing these pseudo labels. During training, available coarse\nlabels (e.g., machine-type labels) and data augmentation are\njointly used to further improve performance. Additionally,\nwe propose lightweight noise-robust feature transformation\n(NRFT) methods as a preprocessing step to suppress the\neffects of noise contained in the training data. NRFT uses a\nlinear transformation estimated using a small amount of clean\nmachine-sound data or isolated noise data.\nThe pseudo-label distillation approach itself was proposed\nin our previous work [22]. Subsequent studies have also\nexplored related techniques, including iterative pseudo-label\ngeneration in a discriminative feature space [30], multipseudo-label assignment [31], and domain-adaptive pretraining of teacher SSL models [32]. In contrast, this paper focuses on the original, simple pseudo-label distillation framework and conducts comprehensive evaluations and analyses\nto provide a deeper understanding. Our contributions are\nsummarized as follows:\n• We conduct comprehensive evaluations across the\nDCASE 2020–2025 datasets using four state-of-the-art\n2\n\n(SOTA) SSL models. The experimental results show\nthat pseudo-label distillation effectively transfers the\nperformance of SSL models to smaller discriminative\nfrontends while reducing the number of parameters and\nmultiply-accumulate operations (MACs) to less than\n10% of those of the original SSL models.\n• We show that pseudo-label distillation can achieve even\nbetter performance than the original SSL models by\nutilizing available coarse labels and data augmentation.\n• We further show that the performance gains from\npseudo-label distillation are observed not only when\ntraining small discriminative frontends from scratch but\nalso when fine-tuning SSL models.\n• We propose lightweight NRFT methods that construct\nnoise-robust feature spaces for pseudo-label generation\nusing a small amount of clean machine sounds or isolated noise samples.\n1\n• We publish the code in ASDKit [7].\nII. RELATED WORK\n\nMany methods have been proposed to obtain effective feature spaces for ASD. Discriminative approaches have been\nimproved in terms of loss functions, data augmentation, and\nnetwork architectures. In terms of loss functions, angularmargin losses such as ArcFace [33] and AdaCos [34] have\nbeen commonly employed for the ASD task. These losses\nencourage the features of each class to form compact and\nwell-separated clusters, which has been shown to be effective\nfor the downstream ASD task [23]. In addition, less restrictive\nfeature distributions have been shown to further improve ASD\nperformance. Such distributions can be learned using Subcluster AdaCos (SCAC) [23], which introduces multiple class\ncenters for each class, and trainable class centers rather than\nfixed centers [7]. For data augmentation, mixup [35] has been\nwidely used and shown to improve ASD performance [7]. Regarding network architectures, lightweight CNN-based networks have been commonly used [2], [3], [11], [12], [14],\n[36]. The DCASE Challenge Task 2 baseline [2], [3] employed MobileNetV2 [36] with log-mel spectrogram input,\nand an extension using waveform input has been shown to\nimprove performance [14]. Multi-branch architectures comprising spectrogram and spectrum branches have also been\nwidely adopted [11], [12], with further improvements reported using multi-resolution spectrogram inputs [22]. These\ndiscriminative models are trained from scratch on machinesound datasets and are considerably more lightweight than\nSSL models.\nFor SSL-based approaches, many SSL models have been\nemployed for ASD. BEATs [24] is one of the most widely\nused SSL models for various audio tasks, including ASD [16],\n[17], [19], [37]. It is trained through masked audio prediction\nin a discrete token space, with the tokenizer and SSL model\niteratively updated through knowledge distillation. EAT [25]\nis another SSL model widely used for ASD [16], [17], [37]. It\n1 https://github.com/TakuyaFujimura/dcase-asd-toolkit\nVOLUME 11, 2023\n\n\fT. Fujimura et al.: Pseudo-label distillation for discriminative anomalous sound detection\n\nis based on a masked bootstrapping framework and employs\na CLS token and an utterance-level loss to capture global\ninformation. Dasheng is a recent large-scale SSL model with\napproximately 1.2B parameters. It is trained using a masked\nautoencoder framework on 272k hours of audio data. These\naudio SSL models are trained on diverse audio datasets\nspanning speech, music, and environmental sounds and have\nbeen shown to achieve better ASD performance than speechand music-specific SSL models [21], [27]. More recently,\nSSL models specifically designed for machine signals have\nalso been proposed [27], [38]. These models are designed\nto handle arbitrary sampling rates and have shown strong\nperformance on fault-diagnosis benchmarks. Despite these\nadvantages, the aforementioned general-purpose audio SSL\nmodels have still demonstrated comparable or better ASD\nperformance [27], highlighting their strong generalization\ncapabilities.\nIII. PSEUDO-LABEL DISTILLATION\nA. OVERVIEW\n\nPseudo-label distillation first extracts SSL features from normal training data. We employ the following four SSL models:\nBEATs [24] (BEATs_iter3.pt), a version of BEATs fine-tuned\nfor audio tagging (BEATs_iter3_plus_AS2M_finetuned_on_\nAS2M_cpt1.pt), EAT [25] (EAT-base_epoch10_pt.pt), and\nDasheng [26] (dasheng-1.2B). These SSL models receive a\nsequence of mel-spectrogram patches or segments and output\nthe corresponding feature sequence. For BEATs and Dasheng,\nwe average the SSL feature sequence to obtain a single feature\nvector for each audio sample, whereas for EAT, we use the\nCLS token. To generate pseudo labels, we apply k-means\nclustering, with the number of clusters determined from the\nnumber of training samples using the cluster ratio r. We\nevaluate several values of r, as well as an oracle setting in\nwhich the best value of r is selected separately for each\nmachine type.\nTo not only reduce computational cost but also further\nimprove performance, we jointly use available coarse labels\nduring pseudo-label distillation. In the experiments, we use\nthe machine-type labels provided in the DCASE datasets [1]–\n[6] as coarse labels. Using these coarse labels, we perform\nclustering separately for each coarse-label class and combine the resulting pseudo labels to construct a multi-class\nclassification task for distillation. For example, the DCASE\n2023 dataset contains 14 machine types, each with 1,000\nnormal training samples. Thus, setting r = 0.2% yields 2\npseudo-label classes per machine type, resulting in a multiclass classification task with 28 classes in total. Additionally,\nmotivated by the Noisy Student framework [39], we employ\nmixup as data augmentation during pseudo-label distillation.\nB. NOISE-ROBUST FEATURE TRANSFORMATION (NRFT)\n\nIn the experimental evaluations in Sect. IV, we show\nthat pseudo-label distillation can sometimes degrade performance. This degradation occurs because the training data\nconsist of noisy machine sounds, and the SSL features capture\nVOLUME 11, 2023\n\nnot only machine characteristics but also noise characteristics. When noise conditions vary across training samples and\nthe noise dominates the machine sound, the resulting pseudo\nlabels primarily reflect differences in noise conditions rather\nthan machine characteristics. Such noise-dependent pseudo\nlabels make the student frontend sensitive to noise variations,\nthereby degrading performance.\nTo address this issue, we propose a lightweight noiserobust feature transformation (NRFT) method for pseudolabel generation. In general, improving noise robustness requires auxiliary information about either noise or clean target\nsounds. In this work, we consider the setting of DCASE 2025\nTask 2 [6], where a small number of either clean machinesound samples or isolated noise samples are available for each\nmachine type.\nFor the case where clean machine sounds are available,\nwe propose a principal component analysis (PCA)-based\nsubspace projection. We first extract SSL features from the\nclean machine sounds and apply PCA to the extracted clean\nfeatures. We then construct a projection matrix V ∈ RD×K\nusing the top K principal components, where D denotes the\nfeature dimension. The SSL features of the noisy machine\nsounds in the training data are projected onto this subspace,\nand clustering is then performed to obtain pseudo labels. This\nprojection suppresses components that are less representative\nof the clean machine sounds and are therefore likely to reflect\nnoise-related variations.\nFor the case where isolated noise samples ar", "stderr": "\nShell cwd was reset to /inspire/qb-ilm/project/video-generation/chenxie-25019/hyr/iHateTheWorld555.github.io", "interrupted": false, "isImage": false, "noOutputExpected": false}}
{"type": "assistant", "message": {"id": "msg_1784636278907", "type": "message", "role": "assistant", "content": [{"type": "tool_use", "id": "chatcmpl-tool-898bda0e7094cbcd", "name": "Bash", "input": {"command": "cd /tmp && python3 -c \"\nimport subprocess\nresult = subprocess.run(['pdftotext', 'paper_2607.16678.pdf', '-'], capture_output=True, text=True)\nprint(result.stdout[15000:30000])\n\" 2>&1 | head -400", "description": "Extract second portion of PDF text"}}], "model": "GLM-5.2-w4a8", "stop_reason": null, "stop_sequence": null, "usage": {"input_tokens": 0, "output_tokens": 0, "cache_creation_input_tokens": 0, "cache_read_input_tokens": 0}, "context_management": null}, "parent_tool_use_id": null, "session_id": "19e31ec3-fea2-4fd0-b28f-598d48d170a2", "uuid": "758ef067-2473-4e6e-9456-64e5dd38e59f"}
{"type": "user", "message": {"role": "user", "content": [{"tool_use_id": "chatcmpl-tool-898bda0e7094cbcd", "type": "tool_result", "content": "e available, we\npropose a generalized eigenvalue decomposition (GEVD)based method. We aim to obtain a feature transformation\nthat preserves variations in noisy machine sounds while suppressing directions dominated by noise. The corresponding\ntransformation direction v ∈ RD is obtained by solving the\nfollowing optimization problem:\nmax\nv\n\nv⊤ Rx v\n,\nv ⊤ Rn v\n\n(1)\n\nwhere Rx ∈ RD×D and Rn ∈ RD×D denote the covariance\nmatrices of the SSL features of the noisy machine sounds\nand the isolated noise samples, respectively. This problem is\nsolved by GEVD, leading to the following problem:\nRx v = λRn v.\n\n(2)\n\nThe eigenvalue λ represents the ratio of the variance of the\nnoisy machine sound features to that of the noise features\nalong direction v. The transformation matrix V ∈ RD×K\nis constructed from the eigenvectors corresponding to the K\nlargest eigenvalues. These eigenvectors are normalized such\nthat V⊤ Rn V = I, where I denotes the identity matrix.\nWhen K < D, this transformation projects the features onto\na noise-robust subspace. When K = D, the transformation\ncorresponds to whitening with respect to the noise covariance\nmatrix Rn , without dimensionality reduction. In practice,\ndue to the limited size of the isolated-noise dataset, we first\nperform PCA using the features of both the noisy machine\n3\n\n\fT. Fujimura et al.: Pseudo-label distillation for discriminative anomalous sound detection\n\nsounds and isolated noise samples, reducing the feature dimension to D = 64. We then solve Eq. (1) in the reduced\nfeature space.\n\nTABLE 1. Methods used in the experiments. The suffix of each\nDis-single-*, Dis-multi-*, and Dis-SSL-* is either machine, GT, PL, or NRFT,\nindicating the use of coarse machine-type labels, detailed ground-truth\nlabels, pseudo labels, or pseudo labels generated with NRFT, respectively.\n\nIV. EXPERIMENTAL EVALUATION\n\nMethod name\n\nDescription\n\nWe conduct extensive analyses of pseudo-label distillation. In Sect. IV-B1, we comprehensively evaluate pseudolabel distillation across the DCASE 2020–2025 datasets using four SSL models and analyze its computational cost.\nIn Sect. IV-B2, we analyze the effects of using coarse\nmachine-type labels and mixup during pseudo-label distillation. In Sect. IV-B3, we also evaluate the use of pseudo\nlabels for fine-tuning SSL models, focusing on performance improvement rather than computational cost reduction. In Sect. IV-B4, we evaluate our NRFT methods.\n\nDis-single-*\nDis-multi-*\nRaw-SSL\nDis-SSL-*\n\nDiscriminative frontend using a single-resolution spectrogram\nDiscriminative frontend using multi-resolution spectrograms\nDirect use of original SSL features\nDiscriminative fine-tuning of an SSL model\n\nA. SETUPS\n\nWe conducted experimental evaluations on the DCASE\n2020–2025 Task 2 datasets [1]–[6]. These datasets are constructed from different data sources: [40] and [41] for 2020;\n[42] and [43] for 2021; [44] and [43] for 2022; [44], [43],\nand [45] for 2023; [44], [43], [46], and [47] for 2024; and\n[44], [43], and [48] for 2025. The recordings are 6–18-second\nsingle-channel audio samples recorded at 16 kHz. Each\ndataset contains several machine types. The DCASE 2020–\n2022 datasets include 6–7 machine types, and each machine\ntype has 6–7 subsets called sections. Each section consists of\ntraining data with approximately 1,000 normal-sound samples and test data with approximately 100–200 samples for\neach of the normal and anomalous conditions. The DCASE\n2023–2025 datasets include 14–16 machine types, and each\nmachine type has a single section. The DCASE 2025 dataset\nadditionally provides 100 samples of clean machine sounds\nor isolated noise for each machine type, which can be used\nfor NRFT. For all datasets, sections and machine types are\ngrouped into dev and eval subsets, and the evaluation results\nare aggregated and reported separately for each subset.\nWe followed the official evaluation metrics for each\ndataset. In DCASE 2020, area under the receiver operating\ncharacteristic (ROC) curve (AUC) and partial AUC (pAUC)\nwith p = 0.1 are calculated for each section. These scores are\nthen aggregated by taking the arithmetic mean across sections\nand machine types to obtain machine-type-wise scores and\ndev/eval-wise scores. For DCASE 2021–2025, a domain shift\nproblem [49] has been introduced, in which the recording\nenvironments and machine operating conditions differ between the source and target domains. While the target domain\nincludes only approximately 1% as many training samples as\nthe source domain, the test data include the same number of\nsamples from both domains, requiring models to generalize\nacross domains. In DCASE 2021, AUC and pAUC are calculated for each domain. These scores are then aggregated\nby taking the harmonic mean across sections, domains, and\nmachine types. In DCASE 2022–2025, AUC is calculated\nfor each domain, whereas pAUC is calculated using samples\nfrom both domains. These scores are aggregated using the\n4\n\nharmonic mean. Further details of the task setups are provided\nin the original papers [1]–[6], and the setups for DCASE\n2020–2024 are also summarized in [7].\nThe DCASE datasets include coarse machine-type labels\nand more detailed labels (e.g., machine IDs and attributes). To\nsimulate unlabeled conditions, we concealed all labels except\nfor the machine-type labels. In the DCASE 2024 and 2025\ndatasets, approximately half of the machine types are originally provided with only machine-type labels, and we also\nconducted evaluations using these public benchmark setups.\nFor pseudo-label generation, we varied the cluster ratio r over\n0.2, 0.4, 0.8, 1.6, 3.2, 6.4, and 12.8%.\nFor the student discriminative frontend, we used two multibranch architectures [11], [12], [22]. One used spectrum and\nsingle-resolution spectrogram inputs computed using a shorttime Fourier transform (STFT) with a discrete Fourier transform (DFT) size of 1024, whereas the other used spectrum\nand multi-resolution spectrogram inputs [22] computed using\nSTFTs with DFT sizes of 256, 1024, and 4096. The hop size\nfor each STFT was set to half the corresponding DFT size.\nWe trained each network for 16 epochs using SCAC with 16\nsub-clusters, the AdamW optimizer [50], a fixed learning rate\nof 0.001, and a batch size of 64. The mixup probability was\nset to 0.5.\nFor fine-tuning BEATs and EAT in Sect. IV-B3, we used\nlow-rank adaptation (LoRA) [51]. For BEATs, we introduced\nLoRA parameters into the query and key projections in the\nTransformer layers. The output feature sequence was transformed into a single 256-dimensional discriminative feature\nusing an attentive statistics pooling layer [52] and a linear\nlayer. For EAT, we introduced LoRA parameters into the\nquery, key, and value projections. The CLS token was transformed into a single 256-dimensional discriminative feature\nusing a linear layer. We fine-tuned the models for 25 epochs\nusing SCAC, the AdamW optimizer, a batch size of 8, and a\nLoRA rank of 64. During the initial 5,000 steps, the learning\nrate was increased linearly from 0 to 0.0001.\nFor the backend, we employed a standard nearestneighbor-based approach with SMOTE oversampling [7].\nWe calculated the nearest-neighbor distance between a test\nsample and normal training samples in the feature space as\nthe anomaly score. To mitigate the data imbalance between\nthe source and target domains, SMOTE oversampling [53]\nwas applied to the target-domain training samples in the feature space. Specifically, we oversampled the target-domain\nsamples using two nearest neighbors until the number of\nVOLUME 11, 2023\n\n\fT. Fujimura et al.: Pseudo-label distillation for discriminative anomalous sound detection\n\n2020\n\nBEATs\n\n2021\n\n2022\n\n2023\n\n2024\n\n2025\n\nAverage\n\nDis-multi-machine 76.27\n(0.65)\n\n80.94\n\n59.66 60.41\n\n60.41 56.77\n\n58.04 57.22\n\n58.26 51.69\n\n54.01 52.05\n(2.43)\n\n60.48 56.85\n\nRaw-SSL (cosine) 70.43\n\n71.40\n\n62.85 58.12\n\n61.86 57.08\n\n60.71 64.15\n\n58.54 55.58\n\n61.12 59.16\n\nRaw-SSL (euclid) 71.09\n\n72.08\n\n62.92 58.65\n\n61.94 57.36\n\n(1.88)\n\n(0.78)\n\n0.90\n\n79.80\nDis-multi-PL (r=0.8%) 75.86\n(0.74)\n(1.16)\n\n(1.75)\n\n60.08 59.25\n(0.75)\n\n+ensemble 76.86\n\n80.98\n81.86\n\nRaw-SSL (cosine) 64.93\n\n67.27\n\n56.86 57.00\n\nRaw-SSL (euclid) 64.67\n\n66.80\n\nDis-multi-PL (r=0.8%) 73.28\n(0.84)\n\n75.76\n\n+ensemble 73.85\n\n76.58\n\nBEATs-FT\n\n0.85\n\n(0.54)\n\n77.72\nDis-multi-PL (oracle) 75.05\n(0.32)\n(0.31)\n\n(0.60)\n\n(1.03)\n\n65.08 64.39\n\n61.19 61.27\n\n67.75 65.08\n\n60.91 63.60\n\n56.19 57.74\n\n59.36 54.93\n\n62.56 61.72\n\n60.54 55.04\n\n59.18 55.11\n\n(0.90)\n\n(0.30)\n\n65.95 63.08\n\n59.54 55.85\n\n58.99 57.57\n\n56.76 56.96\n\n59.52 55.36\n\n57.92 56.10\n\n59.27 56.00\n\n58.93 57.57\n\n59.76 60.10\n\n64.16 61.59\n\n59.46 58.40\n0.66\n63.50 61.68\n\n65.24 62.39\n\n64.43 62.70\n66.01 65.48\n\n(1.00)\n\n60.32 60.93\n\n(1.75)\n\n0.64\n\n(1.10)\n\n67.64 63.98\n\n(0.82)\n\n(0.58)\n\n(0.86)\n\n77.74\n\n58.72 58.95\n\n63.55 62.45\n\n+ensemble 74.42\n\n78.77\n\n59.15 59.66\n\n64.33 62.93\n\nDis-multi-PL (oracle) 75.20\n(0.99)\n\n79.54\n\n59.73 61.62\n\nRaw-SSL (cosine) 62.28\n\n62.14\n\n(0.28)\n\n(0.13)\n\n0.62\n\n(0.63)\n\n(0.24)\n\n57.74 55.91\n\n0.64\n\n(1.41)\n\n(0.81)\n\n56.60 60.97\n\n57.89 56.43\n\n57.10 60.37\n\n(0.46)\n\n66.91 64.08\n(1.01)\n\n0.62\n\n(1.37)\n\n58.41 55.41\n\n62.64 59.84\n\n60.89 57.05\n\n60.66 59.20\n\n64.52 61.95\n\n57.75 57.45\n\n58.67 54.90\nShell cwd was reset to /inspire/qb-ilm/project/video-generation/chenxie-25019/hyr/iHateTheWorld555.github.io", "is_error": false}]}, "parent_tool_use_id": null, "session_id": "19e31ec3-fea2-4fd0-b28f-598d48d170a2", "uuid": "dbfb5396-f13c-4658-a873-6a5dcd401fb1", "timestamp": "2026-07-21T12:18:06.246Z", "tool_use_result": {"stdout": "e available, we\npropose a generalized eigenvalue decomposition (GEVD)based method. We aim to obtain a feature transformation\nthat preserves variations in noisy machine sounds while suppressing directions dominated by noise. The corresponding\ntransformation direction v ∈ RD is obtained by solving the\nfollowing optimization problem:\nmax\nv\n\nv⊤ Rx v\n,\nv ⊤ Rn v\n\n(1)\n\nwhere Rx ∈ RD×D and Rn ∈ RD×D denote the covariance\nmatrices of the SSL features of the noisy machine sounds\nand the isolated noise samples, respectively. This problem is\nsolved by GEVD, leading to the following problem:\nRx v = λRn v.\n\n(2)\n\nThe eigenvalue λ represents the ratio of the variance of the\nnoisy machine sound features to that of the noise features\nalong direction v. The transformation matrix V ∈ RD×K\nis constructed from the eigenvectors corresponding to the K\nlargest eigenvalues. These eigenvectors are normalized such\nthat V⊤ Rn V = I, where I denotes the identity matrix.\nWhen K < D, this transformation projects the features onto\na noise-robust subspace. When K = D, the transformation\ncorresponds to whitening with respect to the noise covariance\nmatrix Rn , without dimensionality reduction. In practice,\ndue to the limited size of the isolated-noise dataset, we first\nperform PCA using the features of both the noisy machine\n3\n\n\fT. Fujimura et al.: Pseudo-label distillation for discriminative anomalous sound detection\n\nsounds and isolated noise samples, reducing the feature dimension to D = 64. We then solve Eq. (1) in the reduced\nfeature space.\n\nTABLE 1. Methods used in the experiments. The suffix of each\nDis-single-*, Dis-multi-*, and Dis-SSL-* is either machine, GT, PL, or NRFT,\nindicating the use of coarse machine-type labels, detailed ground-truth\nlabels, pseudo labels, or pseudo labels generated with NRFT, respectively.\n\nIV. EXPERIMENTAL EVALUATION\n\nMethod name\n\nDescription\n\nWe conduct extensive analyses of pseudo-label distillation. In Sect. IV-B1, we comprehensively evaluate pseudolabel distillation across the DCASE 2020–2025 datasets using four SSL models and analyze its computational cost.\nIn Sect. IV-B2, we analyze the effects of using coarse\nmachine-type labels and mixup during pseudo-label distillation. In Sect. IV-B3, we also evaluate the use of pseudo\nlabels for fine-tuning SSL models, focusing on performance improvement rather than computational cost reduction. In Sect. IV-B4, we evaluate our NRFT methods.\n\nDis-single-*\nDis-multi-*\nRaw-SSL\nDis-SSL-*\n\nDiscriminative frontend using a single-resolution spectrogram\nDiscriminative frontend using multi-resolution spectrograms\nDirect use of original SSL features\nDiscriminative fine-tuning of an SSL model\n\nA. SETUPS\n\nWe conducted experimental evaluations on the DCASE\n2020–2025 Task 2 datasets [1]–[6]. These datasets are constructed from different data sources: [40] and [41] for 2020;\n[42] and [43] for 2021; [44] and [43] for 2022; [44], [43],\nand [45] for 2023; [44], [43], [46], and [47] for 2024; and\n[44], [43], and [48] for 2025. The recordings are 6–18-second\nsingle-channel audio samples recorded at 16 kHz. Each\ndataset contains several machine types. The DCASE 2020–\n2022 datasets include 6–7 machine types, and each machine\ntype has 6–7 subsets called sections. Each section consists of\ntraining data with approximately 1,000 normal-sound samples and test data with approximately 100–200 samples for\neach of the normal and anomalous conditions. The DCASE\n2023–2025 datasets include 14–16 machine types, and each\nmachine type has a single section. The DCASE 2025 dataset\nadditionally provides 100 samples of clean machine sounds\nor isolated noise for each machine type, which can be used\nfor NRFT. For all datasets, sections and machine types are\ngrouped into dev and eval subsets, and the evaluation results\nare aggregated and reported separately for each subset.\nWe followed the official evaluation metrics for each\ndataset. In DCASE 2020, area under the receiver operating\ncharacteristic (ROC) curve (AUC) and partial AUC (pAUC)\nwith p = 0.1 are calculated for each section. These scores are\nthen aggregated by taking the arithmetic mean across sections\nand machine types to obtain machine-type-wise scores and\ndev/eval-wise scores. For DCASE 2021–2025, a domain shift\nproblem [49] has been introduced, in which the recording\nenvironments and machine operating conditions differ between the source and target domains. While the target domain\nincludes only approximately 1% as many training samples as\nthe source domain, the test data include the same number of\nsamples from both domains, requiring models to generalize\nacross domains. In DCASE 2021, AUC and pAUC are calculated for each domain. These scores are then aggregated\nby taking the harmonic mean across sections, domains, and\nmachine types. In DCASE 2022–2025, AUC is calculated\nfor each domain, whereas pAUC is calculated using samples\nfrom both domains. These scores are aggregated using the\n4\n\nharmonic mean. Further details of the task setups are provided\nin the original papers [1]–[6], and the setups for DCASE\n2020–2024 are also summarized in [7].\nThe DCASE datasets include coarse machine-type labels\nand more detailed labels (e.g., machine IDs and attributes). To\nsimulate unlabeled conditions, we concealed all labels except\nfor the machine-type labels. In the DCASE 2024 and 2025\ndatasets, approximately half of the machine types are originally provided with only machine-type labels, and we also\nconducted evaluations using these public benchmark setups.\nFor pseudo-label generation, we varied the cluster ratio r over\n0.2, 0.4, 0.8, 1.6, 3.2, 6.4, and 12.8%.\nFor the student discriminative frontend, we used two multibranch architectures [11], [12], [22]. One used spectrum and\nsingle-resolution spectrogram inputs computed using a shorttime Fourier transform (STFT) with a discrete Fourier transform (DFT) size of 1024, whereas the other used spectrum\nand multi-resolution spectrogram inputs [22] computed using\nSTFTs with DFT sizes of 256, 1024, and 4096. The hop size\nfor each STFT was set to half the corresponding DFT size.\nWe trained each network for 16 epochs using SCAC with 16\nsub-clusters, the AdamW optimizer [50], a fixed learning rate\nof 0.001, and a batch size of 64. The mixup probability was\nset to 0.5.\nFor fine-tuning BEATs and EAT in Sect. IV-B3, we used\nlow-rank adaptation (LoRA) [51]. For BEATs, we introduced\nLoRA parameters into the query and key projections in the\nTransformer layers. The output feature sequence was transformed into a single 256-dimensional discriminative feature\nusing an attentive statistics pooling layer [52] and a linear\nlayer. For EAT, we introduced LoRA parameters into the\nquery, key, and value projections. The CLS token was transformed into a single 256-dimensional discriminative feature\nusing a linear layer. We fine-tuned the models for 25 epochs\nusing SCAC, the AdamW optimizer, a batch size of 8, and a\nLoRA rank of 64. During the initial 5,000 steps, the learning\nrate was increased linearly from 0 to 0.0001.\nFor the backend, we employed a standard nearestneighbor-based approach with SMOTE oversampling [7].\nWe calculated the nearest-neighbor distance between a test\nsample and normal training samples in the feature space as\nthe anomaly score. To mitigate the data imbalance between\nthe source and target domains, SMOTE oversampling [53]\nwas applied to the target-domain training samples in the feature space. Specifically, we oversampled the target-domain\nsamples using two nearest neighbors until the number of\nVOLUME 11, 2023\n\n\fT. Fujimura et al.: Pseudo-label distillation for discriminative anomalous sound detection\n\n2020\n\nBEATs\n\n2021\n\n2022\n\n2023\n\n2024\n\n2025\n\nAverage\n\nDis-multi-machine 76.27\n(0.65)\n\n80.94\n\n59.66 60.41\n\n60.41 56.77\n\n58.04 57.22\n\n58.26 51.69\n\n54.01 52.05\n(2.43)\n\n60.48 56.85\n\nRaw-SSL (cosine) 70.43\n\n71.40\n\n62.85 58.12\n\n61.86 57.08\n\n60.71 64.15\n\n58.54 55.58\n\n61.12 59.16\n\nRaw-SSL (euclid) 71.09\n\n72.08\n\n62.92 58.65\n\n61.94 57.36\n\n(1.88)\n\n(0.78)\n\n0.90\n\n79.80\nDis-multi-PL (r=0.8%) 75.86\n(0.74)\n(1.16)\n\n(1.75)\n\n60.08 59.25\n(0.75)\n\n+ensemble 76.86\n\n80.98\n81.86\n\nRaw-SSL (cosine) 64.93\n\n67.27\n\n56.86 57.00\n\nRaw-SSL (euclid) 64.67\n\n66.80\n\nDis-multi-PL (r=0.8%) 73.28\n(0.84)\n\n75.76\n\n+ensemble 73.85\n\n76.58\n\nBEATs-FT\n\n0.85\n\n(0.54)\n\n77.72\nDis-multi-PL (oracle) 75.05\n(0.32)\n(0.31)\n\n(0.60)\n\n(1.03)\n\n65.08 64.39\n\n61.19 61.27\n\n67.75 65.08\n\n60.91 63.60\n\n56.19 57.74\n\n59.36 54.93\n\n62.56 61.72\n\n60.54 55.04\n\n59.18 55.11\n\n(0.90)\n\n(0.30)\n\n65.95 63.08\n\n59.54 55.85\n\n58.99 57.57\n\n56.76 56.96\n\n59.52 55.36\n\n57.92 56.10\n\n59.27 56.00\n\n58.93 57.57\n\n59.76 60.10\n\n64.16 61.59\n\n59.46 58.40\n0.66\n63.50 61.68\n\n65.24 62.39\n\n64.43 62.70\n66.01 65.48\n\n(1.00)\n\n60.32 60.93\n\n(1.75)\n\n0.64\n\n(1.10)\n\n67.64 63.98\n\n(0.82)\n\n(0.58)\n\n(0.86)\n\n77.74\n\n58.72 58.95\n\n63.55 62.45\n\n+ensemble 74.42\n\n78.77\n\n59.15 59.66\n\n64.33 62.93\n\nDis-multi-PL (oracle) 75.20\n(0.99)\n\n79.54\n\n59.73 61.62\n\nRaw-SSL (cosine) 62.28\n\n62.14\n\n(0.28)\n\n(0.13)\n\n0.62\n\n(0.63)\n\n(0.24)\n\n57.74 55.91\n\n0.64\n\n(1.41)\n\n(0.81)\n\n56.60 60.97\n\n57.89 56.43\n\n57.10 60.37\n\n(0.46)\n\n66.91 64.08\n(1.01)\n\n0.62\n\n(1.37)\n\n58.41 55.41\n\n62.64 59.84\n\n60.89 57.05\n\n60.66 59.20\n\n64.52 61.95\n\n57.75 57.45\n\n58.67 54.90", "stderr": "\nShell cwd was reset to /inspire/qb-ilm/project/video-generation/chenxie-25019/hyr/iHateTheWorld555.github.io", "interrupted": false, "isImage": false, "noOutputExpected": false}}
{"type": "assistant", "message": {"id": "msg_1784636299662", "type": "message", "role": "assistant", "content": [{"type": "tool_use", "id": "chatcmpl-tool-a30096261cdbc347", "name": "Bash", "input": {"command": "cd /tmp && python3 -c \"\nimport subprocess\nresult = subprocess.run(['pdftotext', 'paper_2607.16678.pdf', '-'], capture_output=True, text=True)\nprint(result.stdout[30000:45000])\n\" 2>&1 | head -400", "description": "Extract third portion of PDF text"}}], "model": "GLM-5.2-w4a8", "stop_reason": null, "stop_sequence": null, "usage": {"input_tokens": 0, "output_tokens": 0, "cache_creation_input_tokens": 0, "cache_read_input_tokens": 0}, "context_management": null}, "parent_tool_use_id": null, "session_id": "19e31ec3-fea2-4fd0-b28f-598d48d170a2", "uuid": "79390a85-83e9-419f-af08-c4ef6ed2f508"}
{"type": "user", "message": {"role": "user", "content": [{"tool_use_id": "chatcmpl-tool-a30096261cdbc347", "type": "tool_result", "content": "ort our motivation for\nintroducing pseudo-label distillation.\nPseudo-label distillation effectively transfers the performance of Raw-SSL to the discriminative frontends. Specifically, on the DCASE 2022 eval subset, Dis-multi-machine\nachieves 56.77%, Raw-SSL with BEATs achieves 57.08%,\nand Dis-multi-PL with a fixed cluster ratio of r = 0.8%\nachieves 63.69%, yielding an improvement of approximately\n6 percentage points. Also, Dis-multi-PL achieves the best\naverage performance across all datasets for each of the SSL\nmodels. Even when excluding the exceptional case of DCASE\n2020, in which machine labels provide a large performance\ngain and Dis-multi-machine and Dis-multi-PL substantially\noutperform Raw-SSL, Dis-multi-PL still achieves the best\naverage performance, demonstrating its general effectiveness.\nWe analyze the factors behind this performance improvement in Sect. IV-B2. The performance of pseudo-label distillation is further improved by ensembling the results of\nmultiple training trials, which are easier to perform owing\nto the low computational cost of the student discriminative\nfrontends. Also, the results obtained using the oracle cluster\nratio demonstrate the potential for substantial performance\nimprovement by selecting an appropriate cluster ratio for each\nmachine type.\nTable 2 shows the number of MACs required to process a\n10-second audio signal and the number of parameters for each\nfrontend. BEATs and EAT require over 40 GMACs and 85M\nparameters, and Dasheng requires even more computational\nresources. In contrast, Dis-multi requires only 1.17 GMACs\nand 5M parameters. Moreover, Dis-single further reduces the\ncomputational cost; we show that it still achieves competitive\nperformance in Sect. IV-B2.\nTable 3 shows the evaluation results under the original\nDCASE 2024 and 2025 setups. We generated pseudo labels\nfor machine types with only machine-type labels, while using the original detailed labels for the other machine types.\nFrom the table, we can still see the effectiveness of pseudolabel distillation, even though detailed labels are available\nfor half of the machine types. For example, in terms of average performance, Dis-multi-ORG, which uses the original\npartially missing labels, achieves 58.40%, Raw-SSL with\nBEATs achieves 57.06%, and Dis-multi-PL achieves 59.43%.\nAlso, for DCASE 2025, Dis-multi-PL achieves performance\ncomparable to that of Dis-multi-GT by using pseudo labels\ntogether with the available detailed labels. Furthermore, as in\nFig. 2, pseudo-label distillation substantially improves performance with the oracle cluster ratio.\nOverall, the experimental results across multiple settings\ndemonstrate that pseudo-label distillation effectively transfers the benefits of computationally expensive SSL models\nto compact discriminative frontends, while enabling these\nfrontends to outperform Dis-multi-machine and Raw-SSL.\n\n20dev\n\nT. Fujimura et al.: Pseudo-label distillation for discriminative anomalous sound detection\n\n55\n\n0.2 0.4 0.8 1.6 3.2 6.4 12.8\nCluster ratio [%]\n\n0.2 0.4 0.8 1.6 3.2 6.4 12.8\nCluster ratio [%]\n\nFIGURE 3. Ablation study on the effects of machine-type labels and\nmixup in pseudo-label distillation using BEATs. The average official\nevaluation scores across four trials are shown for each cluster ratio.\n\n2) Analysis of performance gains from pseudo-label\ndistillation\n\nFigure 3 compares different distillation configurations using\nBEATs, examining the effects of multi-resolution spectrograms, machine labels, and mixup. First, although Dis-multi\nachieves the best performance in most cases, Dis-single also\nachieves competitive performance while providing a more\ncompact and efficient frontend, as shown in Table 2. Second,\nboth machine labels and mixup improve performance, particularly on the DCASE 2020–2022 datasets. To investigate\nwhy their benefits differ across datasets, we analyze the original BEATs feature spaces. Figure 4 shows the UMAP [54]\nvisualizations for the DCASE 2020–2025 datasets. The visualizations show that, in the DCASE 2020–2022 datasets, the\nBEATs features of different machine types are more extensively intermixed than those in the other datasets. Figure 5\nshows spectrograms of audio samples selected from the solid\nand dashed rectangles in the DCASE 2020 visualization of\nFig. 4. These examples indicate that samples from different\nmachine types share similar background noise components\nand consequently form clusters based on noise characteristics.\nVOLUME 11, 2023\n\n\fT. Fujimura et al.: Pseudo-label distillation for discriminative anomalous sound detection\n\n2020\n\n0\n\nDim. 2\n\n10\n\nDim. 2\n\n0\n\n5\n\n10\n\n5\n\n20\n\n15\n\nslider\n\n0\n\n5\n\n10 0\n\n5\n\n10 0\n\n5\n\n10 0\n\n5\n\n10 0\n\n5\n\n10 0\n\n5\n\n10\n\n0\n\n5\n\n10 0\n\n5\n\n10 0\n\n5\n\n10 0\n\n5\n\n10 0\n\n5\n\n10 0\n\n5\n\n10\n\nTime [s]\nfan\n\nTime [s]\nfan\n\nTime [s]\npump\n\nTime [s]\npump\n\nTime [s]\nslider\n\nTime [s]\nslider\n\n6\n4\n\n10\n\n2\n\n0\n\n0\n\n10\n\n15\n\n20 2023\n\n0\n\n5\n\n5\n\n10\n\n20\n\n15\n\n10\n0\n10\n20 2024\n\nDim. 2\n\nslider\n\n2\n\n20\n\n15\n\n8\n\n20 2022\n\nDim. 2\n\n10\n\n5\n\n10\n\n10\n\n0\n\n5\n\n5\n\n10\n\n15\n\n10\n\n0\n\n10\n\npump\n\nFrequency [kHz]\n\nDim. 2\n\n2021\n\n0\n\n5\n\n0\n\n20\n\npump\n\n4\n\n10\n\n10\n\nfan\n\n6\n\n0\n\n10\n\nfan\n\n8\n\nFrequency [kHz]\n\nDim. 2\n\n10\n\n10\n\n0\n\n5\n\n2025\n\n10\n\n5\n\n15\n\n20\n\n0\n\nTime [s]\n\nTime [s]\n\nTime [s]\n\nTime [s]\n\nTime [s]\n\nFIGURE 5. Spectrograms of the samples selected from the solid (top) and\ndashed (bottom) rectangles in Fig. 4, respectively. The spectrograms in the\ntop row exhibit similar stationary noise components, for example, around\n1 kHz, whereas those in the bottom row exhibit similar non-stationary\nnoise components around 6 kHz.\n\nmixup contribute to performance improvements. We also\nmentioned that the performance benefits of pseudo-label distillation depend on the SSL feature space, particularly on how\nwell it captures the ground-truth attributes and how robust it\nis to noise variations.\n3) Effectiveness on fine-tuning SSL models\n\n10\n10\n\n5\n\n0\n\nDim. 1\n\n5\n\n10\n\n15\n\nFIGURE 4. UMAP visualizations of the original BEATs features for the\nDCASE 2020–2025 datasets. Colors indicate machine types. Spectrograms\ncorresponding to the samples from the solid and dashed rectangles in the\nDCASE 2020 visualization are shown in Fig. 5.\n\nIn such cases, machine-type classification can encourage the\nfrontend to ignore noise and learn a noise-robust feature\nspace, thereby improving ASD performance [23]. However,\nthis benefit is smaller for DCASE 2023–2025, in which the\nfeature spaces are already separated by machine type.\nWe also analyze differences in the effectiveness of pseudolabel distillation across machine types. Figure 6 shows\nmachine-wise analyses for four machine types from the\nDCASE 2023 dataset. We can see that the characteristics of\nthe feature space differ across machine types, resulting in differences in the effectiveness of pseudo-label distillation and\nthe optimal cluster ratio. For Vacuum and bearing, the BEATs\nfeature spaces clearly reflect the ground-truth attributes, and\npseudo-label distillation substantially improves performance.\nIn contrast, for grinder and shaker, the feature spaces do\nnot clearly reflect the attributes, resulting in only limited\nperformance gains.\nIn this section, we showed that machine-type labels and\nVOLUME 11, 2023\n\nTime [s]\n\nFigure 7 shows the evaluation results for fine-tuning SSL\nmodels using pseudo labels, where each SSL model is finetuned using pseudo labels generated from the original SSL\nmodel. First, fine-tuning using only machine labels can degrade performance compared with the Raw-SSL method, suggesting that catastrophic forgetting can occur. For example,\non the DCASE 2023 eval subset, Raw-SSL with BEATs\nachieves 63.60%, whereas Dis-SSL-machine yields a substantially lower score of 53.78%. In contrast, Dis-SSL-PL\npreserves the performance of Raw-SSL and can further improve upon it. Specifically, Dis-SSL-PL with BEATs achieves\n65.37% on the same subset and achieves the best average\nperformance.\n4) Noise-robust feature transformation\n\nFigure 8 shows the evaluation results for NRFT, where all\nlabels other than the machine-type labels were concealed.\nThe results demonstrate the general effectiveness of NRFT,\nas it outperforms the standard Dis-multi-PL across different\ncluster ratios and SSL models. We can also see that Dis-multiNRFT achieves performance comparable to that of Dis-multiGT. The results aggregated over the clean-data-available case\nshow that smaller values of K are more effective, indicating that restricting the feature space to a lower-dimensional\nclean-sound subspace effectively removes noise-related variations. The results aggregated over the noise-data-available\ncase show that NRFT is still effective with K = D = 64\n7\n\n\fT. Fujimura et al.: Pseudo-label distillation for discriminative anomalous sound detection\n\nOfficial [%]\n\nDis-multi-PL\n90\n80\n70\nShell cwd was reset to /inspire/qb-ilm/project/video-generation/chenxie-25019/hyr/iHateTheWorld555.github.io", "is_error": false}]}, "parent_tool_use_id": null, "session_id": "19e31ec3-fea2-4fd0-b28f-598d48d170a2", "uuid": "6d007650-949f-4c2a-85fb-d696ade170c3", "timestamp": "2026-07-21T12:18:25.397Z", "tool_use_result": {"stdout": "ort our motivation for\nintroducing pseudo-label distillation.\nPseudo-label distillation effectively transfers the performance of Raw-SSL to the discriminative frontends. Specifically, on the DCASE 2022 eval subset, Dis-multi-machine\nachieves 56.77%, Raw-SSL with BEATs achieves 57.08%,\nand Dis-multi-PL with a fixed cluster ratio of r = 0.8%\nachieves 63.69%, yielding an improvement of approximately\n6 percentage points. Also, Dis-multi-PL achieves the best\naverage performance across all datasets for each of the SSL\nmodels. Even when excluding the exceptional case of DCASE\n2020, in which machine labels provide a large performance\ngain and Dis-multi-machine and Dis-multi-PL substantially\noutperform Raw-SSL, Dis-multi-PL still achieves the best\naverage performance, demonstrating its general effectiveness.\nWe analyze the factors behind this performance improvement in Sect. IV-B2. The performance of pseudo-label distillation is further improved by ensembling the results of\nmultiple training trials, which are easier to perform owing\nto the low computational cost of the student discriminative\nfrontends. Also, the results obtained using the oracle cluster\nratio demonstrate the potential for substantial performance\nimprovement by selecting an appropriate cluster ratio for each\nmachine type.\nTable 2 shows the number of MACs required to process a\n10-second audio signal and the number of parameters for each\nfrontend. BEATs and EAT require over 40 GMACs and 85M\nparameters, and Dasheng requires even more computational\nresources. In contrast, Dis-multi requires only 1.17 GMACs\nand 5M parameters. Moreover, Dis-single further reduces the\ncomputational cost; we show that it still achieves competitive\nperformance in Sect. IV-B2.\nTable 3 shows the evaluation results under the original\nDCASE 2024 and 2025 setups. We generated pseudo labels\nfor machine types with only machine-type labels, while using the original detailed labels for the other machine types.\nFrom the table, we can still see the effectiveness of pseudolabel distillation, even though detailed labels are available\nfor half of the machine types. For example, in terms of average performance, Dis-multi-ORG, which uses the original\npartially missing labels, achieves 58.40%, Raw-SSL with\nBEATs achieves 57.06%, and Dis-multi-PL achieves 59.43%.\nAlso, for DCASE 2025, Dis-multi-PL achieves performance\ncomparable to that of Dis-multi-GT by using pseudo labels\ntogether with the available detailed labels. Furthermore, as in\nFig. 2, pseudo-label distillation substantially improves performance with the oracle cluster ratio.\nOverall, the experimental results across multiple settings\ndemonstrate that pseudo-label distillation effectively transfers the benefits of computationally expensive SSL models\nto compact discriminative frontends, while enabling these\nfrontends to outperform Dis-multi-machine and Raw-SSL.\n\n20dev\n\nT. Fujimura et al.: Pseudo-label distillation for discriminative anomalous sound detection\n\n55\n\n0.2 0.4 0.8 1.6 3.2 6.4 12.8\nCluster ratio [%]\n\n0.2 0.4 0.8 1.6 3.2 6.4 12.8\nCluster ratio [%]\n\nFIGURE 3. Ablation study on the effects of machine-type labels and\nmixup in pseudo-label distillation using BEATs. The average official\nevaluation scores across four trials are shown for each cluster ratio.\n\n2) Analysis of performance gains from pseudo-label\ndistillation\n\nFigure 3 compares different distillation configurations using\nBEATs, examining the effects of multi-resolution spectrograms, machine labels, and mixup. First, although Dis-multi\nachieves the best performance in most cases, Dis-single also\nachieves competitive performance while providing a more\ncompact and efficient frontend, as shown in Table 2. Second,\nboth machine labels and mixup improve performance, particularly on the DCASE 2020–2022 datasets. To investigate\nwhy their benefits differ across datasets, we analyze the original BEATs feature spaces. Figure 4 shows the UMAP [54]\nvisualizations for the DCASE 2020–2025 datasets. The visualizations show that, in the DCASE 2020–2022 datasets, the\nBEATs features of different machine types are more extensively intermixed than those in the other datasets. Figure 5\nshows spectrograms of audio samples selected from the solid\nand dashed rectangles in the DCASE 2020 visualization of\nFig. 4. These examples indicate that samples from different\nmachine types share similar background noise components\nand consequently form clusters based on noise characteristics.\nVOLUME 11, 2023\n\n\fT. Fujimura et al.: Pseudo-label distillation for discriminative anomalous sound detection\n\n2020\n\n0\n\nDim. 2\n\n10\n\nDim. 2\n\n0\n\n5\n\n10\n\n5\n\n20\n\n15\n\nslider\n\n0\n\n5\n\n10 0\n\n5\n\n10 0\n\n5\n\n10 0\n\n5\n\n10 0\n\n5\n\n10 0\n\n5\n\n10\n\n0\n\n5\n\n10 0\n\n5\n\n10 0\n\n5\n\n10 0\n\n5\n\n10 0\n\n5\n\n10 0\n\n5\n\n10\n\nTime [s]\nfan\n\nTime [s]\nfan\n\nTime [s]\npump\n\nTime [s]\npump\n\nTime [s]\nslider\n\nTime [s]\nslider\n\n6\n4\n\n10\n\n2\n\n0\n\n0\n\n10\n\n15\n\n20 2023\n\n0\n\n5\n\n5\n\n10\n\n20\n\n15\n\n10\n0\n10\n20 2024\n\nDim. 2\n\nslider\n\n2\n\n20\n\n15\n\n8\n\n20 2022\n\nDim. 2\n\n10\n\n5\n\n10\n\n10\n\n0\n\n5\n\n5\n\n10\n\n15\n\n10\n\n0\n\n10\n\npump\n\nFrequency [kHz]\n\nDim. 2\n\n2021\n\n0\n\n5\n\n0\n\n20\n\npump\n\n4\n\n10\n\n10\n\nfan\n\n6\n\n0\n\n10\n\nfan\n\n8\n\nFrequency [kHz]\n\nDim. 2\n\n10\n\n10\n\n0\n\n5\n\n2025\n\n10\n\n5\n\n15\n\n20\n\n0\n\nTime [s]\n\nTime [s]\n\nTime [s]\n\nTime [s]\n\nTime [s]\n\nFIGURE 5. Spectrograms of the samples selected from the solid (top) and\ndashed (bottom) rectangles in Fig. 4, respectively. The spectrograms in the\ntop row exhibit similar stationary noise components, for example, around\n1 kHz, whereas those in the bottom row exhibit similar non-stationary\nnoise components around 6 kHz.\n\nmixup contribute to performance improvements. We also\nmentioned that the performance benefits of pseudo-label distillation depend on the SSL feature space, particularly on how\nwell it captures the ground-truth attributes and how robust it\nis to noise variations.\n3) Effectiveness on fine-tuning SSL models\n\n10\n10\n\n5\n\n0\n\nDim. 1\n\n5\n\n10\n\n15\n\nFIGURE 4. UMAP visualizations of the original BEATs features for the\nDCASE 2020–2025 datasets. Colors indicate machine types. Spectrograms\ncorresponding to the samples from the solid and dashed rectangles in the\nDCASE 2020 visualization are shown in Fig. 5.\n\nIn such cases, machine-type classification can encourage the\nfrontend to ignore noise and learn a noise-robust feature\nspace, thereby improving ASD performance [23]. However,\nthis benefit is smaller for DCASE 2023–2025, in which the\nfeature spaces are already separated by machine type.\nWe also analyze differences in the effectiveness of pseudolabel distillation across machine types. Figure 6 shows\nmachine-wise analyses for four machine types from the\nDCASE 2023 dataset. We can see that the characteristics of\nthe feature space differ across machine types, resulting in differences in the effectiveness of pseudo-label distillation and\nthe optimal cluster ratio. For Vacuum and bearing, the BEATs\nfeature spaces clearly reflect the ground-truth attributes, and\npseudo-label distillation substantially improves performance.\nIn contrast, for grinder and shaker, the feature spaces do\nnot clearly reflect the attributes, resulting in only limited\nperformance gains.\nIn this section, we showed that machine-type labels and\nVOLUME 11, 2023\n\nTime [s]\n\nFigure 7 shows the evaluation results for fine-tuning SSL\nmodels using pseudo labels, where each SSL model is finetuned using pseudo labels generated from the original SSL\nmodel. First, fine-tuning using only machine labels can degrade performance compared with the Raw-SSL method, suggesting that catastrophic forgetting can occur. For example,\non the DCASE 2023 eval subset, Raw-SSL with BEATs\nachieves 63.60%, whereas Dis-SSL-machine yields a substantially lower score of 53.78%. In contrast, Dis-SSL-PL\npreserves the performance of Raw-SSL and can further improve upon it. Specifically, Dis-SSL-PL with BEATs achieves\n65.37% on the same subset and achieves the best average\nperformance.\n4) Noise-robust feature transformation\n\nFigure 8 shows the evaluation results for NRFT, where all\nlabels other than the machine-type labels were concealed.\nThe results demonstrate the general effectiveness of NRFT,\nas it outperforms the standard Dis-multi-PL across different\ncluster ratios and SSL models. We can also see that Dis-multiNRFT achieves performance comparable to that of Dis-multiGT. The results aggregated over the clean-data-available case\nshow that smaller values of K are more effective, indicating that restricting the feature space to a lower-dimensional\nclean-sound subspace effectively removes noise-related variations. The results aggregated over the noise-data-available\ncase show that NRFT is still effective with K = D = 64\n7\n\n\fT. Fujimura et al.: Pseudo-label distillation for discriminative anomalous sound detection\n\nOfficial [%]\n\nDis-multi-PL\n90\n80\n70", "stderr": "\nShell cwd was reset to /inspire/qb-ilm/project/video-generation/chenxie-25019/hyr/iHateTheWorld555.github.io", "interrupted": false, "isImage": false, "noOutputExpected": false}}
